  ],
  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "The European trading session kill zone (02:00–05:00 EST) that typically delivers the manipulation phase of the daily AMD cycle. London sweeps the prior Asia session range, establishing session highs and lows as key intraday liquidity levels. Its behavior relative to the Asia Range and higher time frame PD Arrays determines the daily profile and sets the stage for New York distribution.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Mark the London session window from 02:00 to 05:00 EST on the intraday chart (verify chart time zone is New York/EST; optionally extend to 08:30 to avoid blank space before the AM session).",
    "Identify the prior Asia session range (20:00–00:00 EST) and determine whether London sweeps one side (Asia high or low) or both sides.",
    "Confirm a London manipulation when price sweeps a high/low and then closes through the opposing candle series (change in state of delivery), often accompanied by aggressive displacement back into the Asia range or SMT divergence with a correlated asset.",
    "If London sweeps one side of the Asia Range, engages a relevant higher time frame PD Array (order block, FVG, or liquidity level), and reverses without sweeping the opposite side, classify as a London Reversal.",
    "If London sweeps both sides of the Asia Range without sustained displacement beyond either side, classify as a Seek and Destroy (non-directional) condition for New York.",
    "If London creates most of the daily range (large expansion in one direction), classify this as a second Seek and Destroy condition for New York, as limited range remains for the NY session.",
    "If London moves directionally but does not reach or engage a relevant higher time frame PD Array, classify the session as a London failure — flag for a New York Reversal setup.",
    "If London consolidates and fails to reach a relevant higher time frame PD array or key level, classify it as accumulation for a potential New York Manipulation profile, expecting New York to later sweep London's range.",
    "Mark the London session high, low, and optionally equilibrium (0.5) as key intraday liquidity reference levels for the New York session.",
    "Mark the London manipulation leg (from the swept extreme to the opposing extreme that created it) for subsequent standard deviation projection use.",
    "Note that an up-close or down-close candle forming during London at the swept extreme can create an order block that may serve as a point of interest during New York.",
    "Note any Change in the State of Delivery forming during London; treat it as a potential false signal if no HTF level was reached."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "London is the manipulation leg of the daily AMD cycle. Anticipate a sweep of the Asia range during 02:00–05:00 EST; confirm reversal via change in state of delivery and SMT divergence. Enter on lower time frame after confirmation, targeting previous day high/low or -2 to -2.5 standard deviation projections of the London manipulation leg. London high/low are key intraday liquidity levels for New York. In Seek and Destroy (both sides swept without displacement), fade into range; if London already expanded the daily range, expect New York consolidation. Stand aside if drawn liquidity targets were already swept in Asia/London.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Attempting to trade directional breakouts during London when price has already swept both sides of the Asia Range, which signals consolidation rather than expansion.",
    "Expecting New York to produce a large directional move when London has already created most of the daily range, leading to low-probability entries.",
    "Trading from inside the range outward during Seek and Destroy conditions instead of fading moves back into the range from outside.",
    "Misclassifying a London Reversal when London forms a swing high or low but never actually engaged a relevant higher time frame PD Array — this is a New York Reversal setup, not a London Reversal.",
    "Acting on a Change in the State of Delivery that forms during London without confirming that a higher time frame level was reached; such signals can be false, leading price to run lows or highs again into New York.",
    "Assuming any high or low formed during 02:00–05:00 EST constitutes a London Reversal without checking whether a higher time frame key level was engaged.",
    "Entering on the initial London sweep without waiting for a confirmed change in state of delivery (closure through opposing candles) and aggressive displacement back into the range.",
    "Ignoring SMT divergence against a correlated asset when assessing whether a London high/low will hold.",
    "Expecting a large directional move during London when it is merely consolidating or has already expanded most of the daily range.",
    "Treating the London session as the distribution move rather than the manipulation phase before New York delivers the real move.",
    "Misaligning chart time zone (e.g., not using New York/EST), causing incorrect marking of the 02:00–05:00 window.",
    "Trying to play breakouts out of the London range on a Seek and Destroy day instead of fading back into the range.",
    "Ignoring high-impact news context (CPI, FOMC, NFP) from the prior day, which often produces Seek and Destroy London behavior.",
    "Trading the New York session when the drawn liquidity target (e.g., previous day high) has already been taken during Asia or London.",
    "Relying solely on the London level as a target when it does not provide minimum 2R, instead of extending with standard deviation projections.",
    "Failing to project the manipulation leg from the swing extreme that created the swept low/high, resulting in incorrect standard deviation targets.",
    "Expecting a London reversal when the daily structure shows expansion-met-with-expansion (a true reversal candle) rather than a manipulation wick.",
    "Treating a London high or low that did not reach a higher time frame key level as a reliable reversal point, rather than liquidity to be swept by New York."
  ],
